A 'shack' is a type of small, often primitive shelter or dwelling. The word may
derive from the Nahuatl (Aztec) word xahcalli or "adobe house" by way of Mexican
Spanish xacal/jacal, which has the same meaning as
"shack".<ref>http://www.bartleby.com/61/75/S0307500.html</ref> It was a common
usage among people of Mexican ancestry throughout the U.S. southwest and was
picked up by speakers of American English.

It is possible that up to a billion people worldwide live in shacks.<ref>Planet
of Slums, Verso, 2006</ref> Fire is a significant hazard in tight-knit shack
settlements.<ref>[http://www.abahlali.org/node/4013 A Big Devil in the Jondolos:
A report on shack fires by Matt Birkinshaw]</ref> Shack settlements are also
sometimes known as slums or shanty towns.
